Prologue
"Please!" Queen Elwin pleaded, "Don't send her away! She's just a child!" The Ice King sat on his throne, looking down at his wife, with the royal advisor standing beside him. The queen had given birth to a girl. At the thought of it, the Ice King couldn't help but furrow his brow.
The infant looked very much like her mother: pale blue eyes, snow-white hair, with a few strands of blue hair. The Ice King thought that having a daughter would make him look weak. After all, before this, he had only a son.
"You only have two choices: either kill the child or leave her in the wilderness. Elwin, this is your punishment," he spat out her name with hatred, as if it were poison. He always did this.
The Frostland Kingdom was not always a kingdom. It once split into two parts, north and south. The north established a non-magical kingdom, while the south was a kingdom full of magical power. Due to the greed of the north, the two kingdoms waged endless wars until the south proposed a truce.
At that time, the southern kingdom had fallen into despair, and royal members were willing to do anything to stop the bloody conflict. They proposed to marry the only princess to the north, making her queen of the north and giving birth to a son as the future king. After that, the south would unite with the north to establish a unified kingdom. The north accepted the proposal, and Princess Elwin was thus married to Prince Akurl.
"Please, my king, for the safety of my child, you can do anything to me—lock me up, exile me, even kill me," Queen Elwin pleaded, hugging her child tightly in her arms.
The Ice King looked down at his queen, his eyes filled with disdain. Perhaps, just perhaps, he would have a little pity for her. After all, this woman had been by his side for 22 years, cared for him during his darkest moments, and bore him children.
"Very well. The child can stay in the palace," the queen sighed in relief upon hearing the Ice King's words. "But," he added, "you will be executed."
The royal advisor and Queen Elwin both showed expressions of fear. She slowly lowered her head, looking at the floor. "As you command, my king," she bowed.
The Ice King ordered the royal advisor to take Queen Elwin's daughter to an empty room assigned to Elwin. Afterward, he commanded the guards to bring Queen Elwin to the execution ground where all citizens could see.
When the guards escorted her to the execution ground, the citizens saw their only queen—also the kindest queen—about to be executed and felt extremely angry. Some cried, others shouted and tried to attack the guards, while others wondered why such a thing had happened; yet they all shared the same question.
"Release her!"
"Why are they treating her like this?"
When Elwin approached the wooden stake, the most feared person in the kingdom appeared. He was the executioner of the stake. The former queen Elwin was to be burned alive. No one should be subjected to the stake, even criminals. In the Frostland Kingdom, burning at the stake was the most cruel punishment.
Elwin was tied to the wooden stake, and the king began to tell how the queen had betrayed them all. The people of the Frostland Kingdom refused to believe, and would never accept the king's words. Then, the executioner lit the stake, and a single tear rolled down the face of the former queen.
"Carly, live on!" Queen Elwin's life came to an end.
The hall was deathly silent.
In the southern wing of this icy palace, an unending "tapping" sound came from the leftmost room. Former servants were always curious about what was inside the room but too afraid to approach. The maids moved around the hall, whispering and spreading various rumors. Some believed that the late queen Elwin, the Ice King's deceased wife, was living in this room, waiting to be released.
They were completely wrong. Avery thought to herself as she walked toward the southern wing, the servants moving along the walls and whispering to each other. They had no idea what was inside.
Of course, there were also many rumors about them, since they were the only one allowed to enter the room.
Knocked on the door. "Miss Carly, are you inside?" Avery whispered softly to the elaborate door, decorated with snowflakes and crowns, symbols of the royal family.
TA didn't know whether she would really let him in this time, which was different from before. I still have the bruises from last time. Avery recalled the incident and couldn't help but smile. At that time, Carly threw a book at him, but as soon as she recognized who it was, she immediately apologized.
A soft sound came from the room, as if saying she couldn't go anywhere, just there.
"May I come in?" Avery asked, unable to forget the consequences of entering uninvited last time.
A soft sound came from the room again. It seemed to say, "Come in." Avery felt a chill, unsure whether it was from the cold or that voice. Although Avery had been there for many years, hearing the sound from the room still made him feel a bit strange.
"I've come in," Avery said, slowly opening the door. By normal standards, the scene inside the room was quite unusual, but it was also expected. The room was filled with paper. Books were scattered on the floor, the table was broken, and there were many ice sculptures around. There were no windows, and almost no light. It was also colder than any other part of the palace (which explained a lot). The room looked as if it had been struck by a blizzard, everything in disarray.
The girl in the room was curled up in bed, wrapped in a blanket, reading a notebook. A small lantern lit up the room.
"Which notebook are you reading?" Avery asked as he sat by Carly's bedside.
